dsa.datastructures.list

Class DynamicArray

  • java.lang.Object
    • dsa.datastructures.list.DynamicArray
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    QueueArray, StackArray

    public class DynamicArray
extends java.lang.Object
    The DynamicArray class contains components that can be accessed using an integer index. However, the size of a DynamicArray can grow or shrink as needed to accommodate adding and removing items after the DynamicArray has been created.

    Each DynamicArray tries to optimize storage management by maintaining a capacity and a capacityIncrement. The capacity is always at least as large as the DynamicArray size; it is usually larger because as components are added to the DynamicArray, the DynamicArray's storage increases in chunks the size of capacityIncrement. An application can increase the capacity of a DynamicArray before inserting a large number of components; this reduces the amount of incremental reallocation.

    DynamicArray is thread-safe and is implemented for primitive types only.

    Time Complexity(Best) Time Complexity(Average) Time Complexity(Worst)
    Insert(add) Ω(1) θ(n) O(n)
    Delete(remove) Ω(1) θ(n) O(n)
    Random Access(get) Ω(1) θ(1) O(1)
    Search(contains) Ω(1) θ(n/2) O(n)
    Sort(sort) Ω(n) θ(n logn) O(n2)

      • ensureCapacity

        public void ensureCapacity(int minCapacity)
        Increases the capacity of this DynamicArray, if necessary, to ensure that it can hold at least the number of components specified by the minimum capacity argument.

        If the current capacity of this DynamicArray is less than minCapacity, then its capacity is increased.

        Parameters:
        minCapacity - the desired minimum capacity

      • trimToSize

        public void trimToSize()
        Trims the capacity of this DynamicArray to be the DynamicArray's current size. If the capacity of this DynamicArray is larger than its current size, then the capacity is changed to equal the size by replacing its internal data array. An application can use this operation to minimize the storage of a DynamicArray.

      • sort

        public void sort(char c)
        Sorts this DynamicArray according to the order specified by the character c.
        Note: Array trims to it's size before sorting.
        Parameters:
        c - if(c == 'a' || c == 'A') then sort a in ascending order, if(c == 'd' || c == 'D') then sort a in descending order
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if((c != 'a' || c != 'A') && (c != 'd' || c != 'D'))

      • sort

        public void sort(int fromIndex,
                 int toIndex,
                 char c)
        Sorts this DynamicArray according to the order specified by the character c.
        Note: Array trims to it's size before sorting.
        Parameters:
        c - if(c == 'a' || c == 'A') then sort a in ascending order, if(c == 'd' || c == 'D') then sort a in descending order
        fromIndex - the index of the first element, inclusive, to be sorted
        toIndex - the index of the last element, exclusive, to be sorted
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if((c != 'a' || c != 'A') && (c != 'd' || c != 'D'))
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if(fromIndex > toIndex)
        java.lang.ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException - if(fromIndex < 0 || toIndex > array.length)

      • toArray

        public java.lang.Object[] toArray()
        Returns an array containing all of the elements in this DynamicArray.

        The returned array will be "safe" in that no references to it are maintained by the DynamicArray. (In other words, this method must allocate a new array). The caller is thus free to modify the returned array.

        Returns:
        an array containing all of the elements in this DynamicArray

        public void zeroFill()
